x4freetext: BNL Tandem Van de Graaff facility.
14C beams of 20-40 nA intensity from tandem Van de
Graaff facility at Brookhaven National Laboratory.
Position-sensitive
telescopes divided into two independent parts:
Frish-grid gas ionization chamber (dE/dx measurement)
and an ORTEC P-series solid state position-sensitive
detector (E measurement), which was placed within a
volume of the ionization chamber gas (P-10 gas at a
pressure of 20 torr).
The early efforts involved 18O beam from Yale`s
accelerator and self-supporting carbon targets highly
enriched (~90%) in 14C. However, this method was
abandoned as too dangerous after the fatigue-induced
bursting of a very thin and necessarily fragile
ionization chamber resulted in the destruction of one
such target inside the scattering chamber. The natural
alternative was to invert beam and target, and the
experiments were carried out at the tandem Van de Graaf
Facility Brookhaven National Laboratory, where
excellent beams of 14C were routinely available.
The uncertainties are purely statistical in
origin.
Approved by S.M. Sterbenz, September 2018.
BP
The primary target was a foil of
oxidized beryllium (B and BeO) approximately 35
microg/cm2 thick. Absolute thicknesses in microg/cm2
particle ratio of 5.9+-0.2 or 85.5%. The secondary
target was of gold, about 100 microg/cm2 thick, and
was used for relative normalization from one angular
distribution to another.
